rows.headline: The Phoenix Police Department said that DNA taken from Nathan Sutherland, 36, a nurse at Hacienda HealthCare, matched that of a boy who was born in December.
rows.description: A nurse at a Phoenix nursing home who had been assigned to care for a woman in a vegetative state who was raped and later gave birth to a child was charged on Wednesday with sexual assault, the police said.

rows.headline: Women’s tennis is giving coaches more prominence in news conferences, on websites and with a Coach of the Year Award, but it draws a line at in-match coaching during Slams.
rows.description: MELBOURNE, Australia — To show a fuller picture of the sport, women’s tennis is shining the spotlight on the coaches who travel the tour with its players.

rows.headline: Mr. Ghosn faces charges in Japan, and his departure will allow the French automaker to focus on mending ties with its longtime Japanese partner.
rows.description: PARIS — Carlos Ghosn has resigned as chairman and chief executive of Renault, according to France’s finance minister, as the French automaker turns its focus to securing the future of the world’s biggest auto alliance.

rows.headline: The show, “Don’t Stop ’Til You Get Enough,” will run this fall, from Oct. 29 to Dec. 1, at the James M. Nederlander Theater.
rows.description: The Michael Jackson musical is taking its first steps onto the dance floor.

rows.headline: James Harris Jackson said he fatally stabbed Timothy Caughman as practice for a terror campaign against blacks who date whites.
rows.description: He hated black men. He wanted to kill one, and he did.

rows.headline: The characters in “Broad City,” “High Maintenance” and “Unbreakable Kimmy Schmidt” have learned to love New York in the era of gentrification.
rows.description: In the first episode of the final season of “Broad City,” BFFs Abbi (Abbi Jacobson) and Ilana (Ilana Glazer) celebrate Abbi’s 30th birthday by walking the length of Manhattan, Inwood to the Battery. They shoot video of dirty water — “city juice” — on the subway tracks. They visit the stately Morris-Jumel Mansion. They get chicken and waffles at Red Rooster in Harlem. They get their hair braided on the sidewalk.

rows.headline: Alan Rusbridger’s “Breaking News” describes his years as the editor of the British newspaper The Guardian, when technological change upended his industry.
rows.description: BREAKING NEWS The Remaking of Journalism and Why It Matters Now By Alan Rusbridger 440 pp. Farrar, Straus & Giroux. $30.

rows.headline: The attack on Khadija Siddiqi, a law student, and her subsequent campaign for justice have led to a national debate.
rows.description: ISLAMABAD, Pakistan — The Pakistan Supreme Court on Wednesday overturned the acquittal of a man accused of stabbing a woman 23 times, nearly three years after the attack prompted a national debate on violence against women.

rows.headline: The former military chief has risen in the polls as he mixes warmongering messages with talk of peace with the Palestinians.
rows.description: JERUSALEM — He kept quiet for months, his poll numbers creeping up against Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu. But Benny Gantz, a former chief of staff of the Israel Defense Forces who is offering himself up as a savior to the opposition, is finally making some noise.

rows.headline: Executives are playing down the threats posed by a trade war and other headwinds, much as they dismissed the possibility of a government shutdown right before it started.
rows.description: America’s corporate leaders are shrugging off a monthslong trade war, a protracted government shutdown and other looming economic threats, projecting that revenue growth in 2019 will be strong largely on the assumption that President Trump will reach a deal with China.

rows.headline: Lithuanian-born, he arrived in New York in 1949 and became a prolific filmmaker, curator, critic and evangelist for independent movies, especially experimental ones.
rows.description: Jonas Mekas, a filmmaker, curator, archivist, critic and all-around evangelist for independently made movies in general, and for those variously known as experimental, underground or avant-garde in particular, died on Wednesday at his home in Brooklyn. He was 96.

rows.headline: Poggy, the street-style-famous creative director of United Arrows & Sons in Tokyo, is helping to introduce a program aimed at promoting Japanese designers to the world.
rows.description: PARIS  — Poggy, also known as Poggy the Man, governmentally known as Motofumi Kogi, is familiar in image and plumage to those who follow men’s fashion, particularly the version of it that walks the streets, not the runway. Street-style photographers have been panting after him for years.

rows.headline: Some U.S. researchers knew of a Chinese scientist’s intentions to implant edited embryos but were unable to stop him. Now scientific institutions are trying to devise global safeguards.
rows.description: A year ago, Dr. Matthew Porteus, a genetics researcher at Stanford, received an out-of-the-blue email from a young Chinese scientist, asking to meet.

rows.headline: Serving in the Lindsay administration, he argued that Lennon was a cultural asset when the Nixon administration tried to deport him in the early 1970s.
rows.description: Edward A. Morrison, a former New York deputy mayor whose avowal that John Lennon was a valuable cultural asset to the city helped Lennon avoid deportation in the 1970s, died on Saturday in Ocala, Fla. He was 85.
